east 14 times higher on days 1, 2, 4, and 8 post-application than mean loadings (0.870.4 ng/cm2) at pre-application. For transferable residues from dog fur, the mean loadings of diazinon on the technician's cotton glove samples were the lowest before application (0.0470.08 ng/cm2) and the highest on day 1 post-application (10.4723.9 ng/cm2) of diazinon to turf. Urinary IMPy concentrations for the participants ranged from o0.3 to 5.5 ng/mL before application and o0.3\textendash 12.5 ng/mL after application of diazinon. The mean urinary IMPy concentrations for children or adults were not statistically different (p40.05) at pre-application compared to post-application of diazinon to turf. The results showed that the participants and their pet dogs were likely exposed to low levels of diazinon residues from several sources (i.e., air, dust, and soil), through several pathways and routes, after lawn applications at these residences. Lastly, the pet dog appears to be an important pathway for the transfer and translocation of diazinon residues inside the homes and likely exposed occupants through personal contacts (i.e., petting).},
